Quote:  The working hours are 10 per diem, and the weather must be very inclement before any stoppage of work ensues, and a 'buckley', or wet holiday, is declared.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1953
Source:  Story of the Kauri, The
Author:  REED
Vol / Page:  135
Edition:
Quote:  These wet-day holidays were known as 'buckleys', but, says an old bushman, "under some contractors and most 'subbers', they were a bit hard to come by". The term "buckleys" is said to have originated from a place called Buckley's Gully, which was always heavily shrouded in mist when a storm was approaching.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1986
Source:  World of the Kauri, The
Author:
Vol / Page:  94
Edition:
Quote:  Only the very wet days - known as "buckleys", after Buckleys Gully, where the weather had traditionally always been bad - were paid days off.
